Hitler was treated several times by Carl Otto von Eicken for 10 years from 1935. The letters are to a cousin. They were found by Robert Doepgen, great-great-grandson of the ear, nose and throat specialist.  Hitler first contacted the doctor in May 1935 convinced that he had throat cancer. It was later discovered that he only had a polyp (growth) about one centimetre in size on the vocal cords. According to the letters, Hitler toldVon Eicken: "If there is something bad, I absolutely have to know." After the assassination attempt on the Fuhrer's life in 1944, the doctor noted, "his physical as well as mental agility and responsiveness had decreased". Von Eicken died in 1960. 